About
London’s Hidden Gem Housing the underground nerve centre where the British government directed the Second World War and the award-winning Churchill Museum, Churchill War Rooms is one of London’s must-see attractions. Walk the top-secret corridors and glimpse what life would have been like during the tense days and nights of the Second World War.
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Westminster
If you only had an afternoon to experience London on a grand scale, Westminster would be a wise place to start. The ornate Houses of Parliament and Westminster Abbey sit adjacent at a corner of Parliament Square, and a short stroll along The Mall leads to Buckingham Palace. Trafalgar Square and Nelson's Column are just up the road as well. As captivating as the architecture is, the wonders of Mother Nature are highlights of the area too. St James's Park (arguably London's loveliest), the expansive Green Park, and pedestrian friendly tree lined paths along the river showcase the exquisite manicure provided by English gardeners. Just beyond the landmarks and the gorgeous outdoor spaces, quiet residential squares and age old local pubs offer a more subdued take on this global seat of power in the heart of London.
How to get there
  • Charing Cross • 9 min walk
  • Embankment • 10 min walk

Cannot Recommend Enough. A must see!
Nov 2024 • Family
This was probably the coolest tour we did on our entire trip to England and France. This tour was so incredibly informative, and did such an amazing job putting you into the experience (as much as possible) of the people who lived through this event. I cannot recommend this tour enough, it's absolutely worth the trip and cost and should be completed for anyone who is remotely interested in World War 2 history.

We had a "semi-private" tour with Mike. He was amazing. He was very clearly passionate about the subject and deeply knowledgeable. He did a remarkable job explaining all the details of the War Rooms and answered every question asked of him with extreme clarity and to each person's requested extent. I feel very lucky that he was our guide for this tour.

The exhibits were wonderful, and are well preserved, so guests can see both the previous function of the location, as well as it's relevance to today. I think if I did this tour again, I would probably learn even more as we did not have time to go back and see more of the museum.

centralscrutiniser
Solihull, UK44 contributions
Content - great. Visitor experience - poor.
Nov 2024 • Family
There are two distinct elements to our thoughts on the war rooms.

1) the content. The chance to see these rooms is brilliant, and the fact that they are so authentically presented is outstanding. It's a really worthwhile thing to see if you have any interest in the period so I highly recommend it.

2) The visitor experience, however, is awful. It's one long enourmous queue crushed into small corridoors. The numbers were vastly oversold meaning that it felt more like being in a rush hour tube station than a museum. Everyone has to wear the audio tour headphones as there is nothing written down, meaning that to see anything you have to crane your neck over the crowd and resist being shoved aside by others to get a glimpse of what you've come to see. The Churchill museum section added little and felt like a way of trying to stretch the experience out a bit to justify the cost.

Given all these issues it was hard to imagine the scene in the 1940s and to get a sense of or appreciate for what the place was. It felt like a missed opportuity to us and after half way through we were ready to leave (except we couldn't, because the corridoors were literally packed with bodies, many of whom were shoving their way through).

You did get the genuine 1940s border guard experience at the check in desk however, as one member of our party was obliged to show a number of emails with his name on in the absence of any credit cards or identification, to authenticate his IWM membership. This wasn't even mentioned at HMS Belfast earlier in the day.

So, something truly worthwhile to see but such a poor experience that it's not a place we will be returning to. I suspect that a quieter day (if such a thing exists in London?) would have meant this was less of an issue, but that's how we found it.
Written November 11, 2024

MadMac66
Fullerton, CA67 contributions
Glad we did it but overall, honestly a bit disapointing for the price
Sep 2024 • Couples
My wife and I visited in early September 2024. We booked our tickets in advance and arrived in plenty of time to be at the front of the queue before the museum opened. Thankfully. I would not recommend doing otherwise.

Being our first vacation without child, we expected all the kids to be back in school so attractions like the War Rooms would be practically empty. How wrong we were. Every other couple now without kids had the same idea as us, and the place (as was every attraction we visited this trip) was PACKED like sardines.

This slightly took the edge off our enjoyment of the tour and museum as we were constantly tripping up and avoiding people. It was hard to get to see everything in the museum, and the audio tour felt rushed as the throng of visitors piled up behind us. We spent two hours here and most of that was dancing around other guests. For the price I don't feel this was overall good value.

All that aside - it’s an unavoidable side-affect of a hugely popular attriaction - the museum is a fascinating insight to the life and work of a man we all know by name, but whom I knew very little actual fact about. The War Rooms tour takes you back to that time, and paints a vivid picture of what it was like down in the bunker, and the sacrifice those working there made. The fact the rooms were left in the state they remain, as the day the war ended, tells us how quick (and no doubt happy) they all were to get out of that place.

The Churchill War Rooms were a fascinating glimpse into the intensity and atmosphere of Britain's war effort during the Second World War. The bunker, where Winston Churchill and his staff planned and coordinated the war, is preserved almost as it was during those critical years. The atmosphere is thick with history, and the exhibits are both informative and engaging. The map room, with its giant wall maps and rows of telephones, was particularly captivating. Enjoy yourself!
